window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"You are provided with a metre rule, a knife edge, two pieces of thread and two masses m1 and m2.  (i) Read and record the values of m1 and m2.  (ii) Balance the metre rule horizontally on the knife edge and record the balance point G.  (iii) With the knife edge at the 60 cm mark of the metre rule, suspend m1 at the 20 cm mark and m2 at a suitable mark such that the rule balances horizontally as illustrated in the diagram above.  (iv) Record the positions Y of m1 and Q of m2.  (v) Evaluate  l  = P - Y and d = Q - P.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of m1 at 18, 16, 14 and 12 cm marks.  (vii) In each case, evaluate and record  l  and d.  (viii) Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph of  l  on the vertical axis against d on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope of the graph.  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"G = 49.5 cm    S/NY(cm)Q(cm) l (cm)d(cm)120.080.040.020.0218.081.042.021.0316.082.044.022.0414.083.046.023.0512.084.048.024.0        Slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 48\u22124024\u221220\\frac{48-40}{24-20}24\u22122048\u221240\u200b = 84\\frac{8}{4}48\u200b = 2    Precautions:  1. I ensured the metre rule was balanced at its center of gravity before taking any readings to achieve accurate results for the moments.    2. I avoided parallax error by keeping my eye level with the pointer when measuring distances from the pivot to the masses.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"With the aid of a diagram, indicate the forces acting on the metre rule in the experimental setup above.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"Define moment of a force about a point and state its S.I unit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The moment of a force about a point is the measure of the tendency of the force to rotate a body around that point. It is the product of the magnitude of the force and the perpendicular distance from the point (pivot) to the line of action of the force. Mathematically, it is given by:  Moment = Force \u00d7 Perpendicular\u00a0distance  The S.I unit of the moment of a force is the Newton meter (Nm).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : PLANE MIRROR","question":"Using the diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions.  (i) Fix the drawing paper provided on the drawing board.  (ii) Place the mirror vertically with its longer side resting on the drawing paper. Trace the outline AB of the mirror. Remove the mirror.  (iii) Draw a normal PQ to meet the outline at the middle Q.  (iv) Draw a straight line through A to meet the outline of the mirror at right angle.  (v) Trace the incident ray, CQ with pins P1 and P2 so that it meets the perpendicular line through A at C such that CA = x = 1.0 cm.  (vi) Replace the mirror on its outline. Locate the images of P1 P2 through the mirror using two other pins P3 and P4, so that P3 and P4 and the images of P1 and P2 are in a straight line.  (vii) Remove the mirror and pins P3 and P4. Draw a straight line through the pin points to meet AB at Q and CA produced at D.  (viii) Measure and record angle ACQ as \u03b81 and angle ADQ as \u03b82. Also record the value of x. Evaluate \u03b8 = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b(\u03b81 + \u03b82), x-1 and tan \u03b8.  (ix) Repeat the procedure for four other values of x = 2.0, 3.0, 4.0 and 5.0 cm. Tabulate your readings.  (x) Plot a graph of tan \u03b8 on the vertical axis against x-1 on the horizontal axis.  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph. Evaluate k = 2s.  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [ Attach your traces to your answer booklet ].","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nx(cm)x-1(cm-1)\u03b8 = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200b(\u03b81 + \u03b82)tan \u03b811.01.0060.01.732122.00.5040.90.886033.00.3330.00.577444.00.2523.40.433055.00.2019.10.3464        Slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 1.7321\u22120.34641\u22120.2\\frac{1.7321-0.3464}{1-0.2}1\u22120.21.7321\u22120.3464\u200b = 1.73    Precautions:  1. I ensured that the pins were accurately aligned with the image before determining their location to avoid parallax error and ensure precise tracing of the ray path.    2. I used sufficient light to illuminate the object clearly, ensuring the formation of a sharp and distinct image for accurate measurement.    3. I placed the pins vertically to avoid any tilting, which could distort the path of the rays and affect the accuracy of my results.    4. I ensured that the object was properly secured and remained stationary during the experiment to prevent any shifts that could affect the alignment of the image and pins.    5. I took multiple measurements to confirm consistency and reduce the likelihood of random errors affecting the final result.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Distinguish between regular and diffused reflections.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Regular reflection occurs when light rays strike a smooth, polished surface, such as a mirror, and are reflected in a uniform, predictable direction. In this case, the reflected rays remain parallel, producing a clear image.    Diffused reflection, on the other hand, occurs when light strikes a rough or uneven surface. The rays are scattered in multiple directions because of the irregularities of the surface, resulting in no clear image being formed.    In summary, regular reflection results in parallel reflected rays and a distinct image, while diffused reflection scatters the rays in different directions, leading to a blurred or no image at all.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : PLANE MIRROR","question":"An object is situated 25 cm in front of a plane mirror. Determine the distance of the image from the object. What is the size of the image relative the object?    (Provide your answers in this format: 123 cm, 20)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"1. Distance of the image: The distance of the image from the mirror is equal to the distance of the object from the mirror. Since the object is 25 cm in front of the mirror, the image will also appear 25 cm behind the mirror.    Therefore, the total distance between the object and its image is:    Distance\u00a0of\u00a0the\u00a0image\u00a0from\u00a0the\u00a0object = 25cm + 25cm = 50cm    2. Size of the image: In a plane mirror, the size of the image is the same as the size of the object. So, the image is equal in size to the object.    \u2234 the size of the image relative the object = 25cm25cm\\frac{25cm}{25cm}25cm25cm\u200b = 1","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a potentiometer XY; a jockey, J; a standard resistor R and other necessary apparatus.  (i) Connect a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Close the key. Read and record the current Io when J is not in contact with XY.  (iii) Let J make contact with XY at C, such that XC =  l  = 25 cm. Close the key. Read and record the current I.  (iv) Evaluate IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b  (v) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  l  = 40, 55, 70 and 85 cm. Tabulate your readings.  (vi) Plot a graph of I on the vertical axis against  l -1 on the horizontal axis.  (vii) From your graph, deduce the value of I when  l -1 = 0. Evaluate IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b.  (viii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Io = 0.10 A    S/N l (cm)I(A) l -1(cm-1)1250.1520.0402400.1600.0253550.1640.0144700.1780.0185850.1900.012        I = 0.19 A when  l -1 = 0    IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b = 0.10.19\\frac{0.1}{0.19}0.190.1\u200b = 0.53    Precautions:  1. I ensured that the key was opened while readings were taken to prevent continuous current flow, which could cause heating and affect the accuracy of the readings.    2. I carefully avoided moving the jockey along the wire unnecessarily to prevent scratching, which could alter the wire's resistance and lead to inaccurate measurements.    3. I ensured that the connections in the circuit were secure and free of loose joints to maintain consistent current flow for accurate readings.    4. I avoided parallax error by aligning my eyes directly with the scale when taking measurements from the meter rule and ammeter to ensure precision.    5. I took multiple readings and averaged them to minimize random errors and increase the reliability of my results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Explain what is meant by potential difference between two points in an electric circuit.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The potential difference between two points in an electric circuit is the amount of electrical energy converted into other forms of energy (such as heat or light) when a unit charge moves between those two points. It represents the driving force that pushes electric charges through the circuit.    The potential difference is measured in volts (V) and is often referred to as voltage. Mathematically, it is given by:    V = WQ\\frac{W}{Q}QW\u200b    where:    V is the potential difference,    W is the work done or energy transferred, and     Q is the charge.    A higher potential difference means a stronger push for electric current to flow between the two points.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2003>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2003","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"A piece of resistance wire of diameter 0.2 mm and resistance 7 \u03a9 has resistivity of 8.8 \u00d7 10-7  \u03a9m. Calculate the length of the wire. [&#960; = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b]    (Provide your answer with the the S.I unit and to 2 decimal places e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"R = \u03c1lA\\frac{\u03c1l}{A}A\u03c1l\u200b    A = \u03c0r2 = \u03c0 (d2)2\\left(\\frac{d}{2}\\right)^{2}(2d\u200b)2    = 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b \u00d7 (0.2\u00d710\u221232)2\\left(\\frac{0.2\u00d710^{-3}}{2}\\right)^{2}(20.2\u00d710\u22123\u200b)2 = 0.314 \u00d7 10-7 m2    l = RA\u03c1\\frac{RA}{\u03c1}\u03c1RA\u200b = 7\u00d70.314\u00d710\u221278.8\u00d710\u22127\\frac{7\u00d70.314\u00d710^{-7}}{8.8\u00d710^{-7}}8.8\u00d710\u221277\u00d70.314\u00d710\u22127\u200b = 0.25 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];